      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I'll stick to the physics from now on.\n\nThe \"beating\" sensation in the minor second is caused by the way the hair cells in the cochlea respond to sound waves. The cochlea is a spiral-shaped structure in the inner ear that converts sound waves into electrical signals that the brain can interpret.\n\nWhen a sound wave with a frequency of 9 Hz is played, the basilar membrane of the cochlea vibrates at that frequency. However, when a sound wave with a frequency of 10 Hz is played, the basilar membrane vibrates at that frequency as well. This is because the two frequencies are close together, and the basilar membrane is sensitive to a range of frequencies.\n\nThe hair cells in the cochlea are responsible for detecting these vibrations. Each hair cell has a specific range of sensitivity, and when the basilar membrane vibrates at a frequency within that range, the hair cell responds by depolarizing and firing an action potential.\n\nWhen the two frequencies (9 Hz and 10 Hz) are close together, the hair cells in the cochlea respond to both frequencies simultaneously. This causes the hair cells to fire at a rate that is the difference between the two frequencies, which is 1 Hz. This is",
